l Versus Semantic Agreement of Greek Hybrid Nouns of the Mädchen Type -- tThe Expression of Authority and Solidarity: ἡμεῖς in Place of ἐγώ in the Iliad -- tA First Approach to Irony in Greek Oratory -- tComparative, Diachronic and Lexicographical Studies -- tGreek Numeral System and Language Contacts in an Archaic Native Settlement of Southern Italy -- tNon-Attic Vocalism, Epichoric Forms, and Attic Poetic Traditions -- tἈμόργινος and ἀμοργίς: The Color of Olive Oil Lees and Aristophanes, Lysistrata 150 and 735, 737 -- tSome Remarks on Ancient Epirote Glosses -- tGreek Papyri and Corpora -- tA Typology of Variations in the Ancient Greek Epistolary Frame (I–III AD) -- tTransposition of Nominal and Verbal Bound Morphemes: The Case of -ες and -ας in Greek Documentary Papyri -- tSome Aspects of Irrealis and the Usage of ἄν in Post-Classical Greek -- tPart II: Latin Language and Linguistics -- tVarious Issues in Latin Linguistics -- tVarro’s Etymological Theory and Practice -- tAn Interplay of Approaches in the Editing of a Late Latin Medical Translation -- tTowards a Unified Account of the ab urbe condita Construction in Latin and Ancient Greek -- tLatin Linguistics and Neronian Pastoral Revisited -- tLinguistics, Philology and Christian Latin -- tNew Concepts in Ancient Languages: Greek and Latin (and beyond) in the First Christian Letters -- tSearching for Order in the Rule: The Contribution of Philology and Linguistics to the Study of Saint Benedict’s Latin -- tList of Contributors -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is a long-standing debate over the relation of historical linguistics and classical philology, especially within the purview of the renewed interest in it during the last decades and the recent trends that characterize philological and linguistic studies. Ever since its appearance in the nineteenth century, the history of this debate testifies to a turbulent coexistence and fertile collaboration of the two disciplines, but at times also moving along centrifugal paths. The essays in this volume address this debate and cover various aspects of linguistic and philological research of Greek and Latin, moving in the middle ground where language, linguistics and philology crosscut and cross-fertilize each other highlighting the application of linguistic theory to the study of classical texts and drawing on fields such as syntactic theory and pragmatics, historical semantics and the lexicon, reconstruction and etymology, dialectology, editorial practices, the use of corpora, and other interdisciplinary approaches that function as hinges between philology and linguistics.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aAltgriechisch. 4aGriechische Linguistik. 4aLatein. 4aLateinische Linguistik. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient Greek and Latin language.  aClassical philology.  aGreek and Latin linguistics.  aHistorical linguistics.1 aAllan, Rutger J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartolo, Giuseppina di, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenedetti, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBentein, Klaas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruno, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCassio, Albio Cesare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConti, Luz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrespo Güemes, Emilio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDosuna, Julián Méndez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato